Though this REALLY needs to be addressed. It's a basic feature that should be supported, especially in pure markdown.. I ended up doing a small bit of custom js:
// Add 'image-link' class to all <a> tags surrounding <img> tags
$('img').parents('a').addClass('image-link');

And the css:
.image-link {
    display: table
    margin: auto
}

.image-link img {
    display: table-cell
}

My selector is actually more descriptive than just 'img' but you can adjust to whatever you need.
This allows [![](path/to/image.png)](path/to/link). I've got a custom theme and have it in a JavaScript file that my theme loads. But the simplest solution might be to edit one of the existing theme templates (like layout.ejs) and put it in a script tag there. (Don't forget to wrap the code in a $(document).ready() call, which is typical for jquery).

